  "prompt": "About traffic rules?",
  "response": "Sure, I can provide an overview of common traffic rules that are followed in many places around the world. Keep in mind that specific traffic laws can vary by country, state, and even city, so it's important to familiarize yourself with the rules in your specific area.\n\n### Basic Traffic Rules:\n\n1. **Speed Limits:** Always observe and adhere to the posted speed limits. Speed limits are set to ensure safety for all road users.\n\n2. **Traffic Signals:** Obey traffic lights\u2014red means stop, green means go, and yellow means caution and prepare to stop.\n\n3. **Stop Signs:** Come to a complete stop at all stop signs, and proceed only when it is safe to do so.\n\n4. **Yield Signs:** Yield to other drivers and pedestrians when you encounter a yield sign.\n\n5. **Right of Way:** Understand and respect right-of-way rules, such as yielding to pedestrians at crosswalks and giving way to vehicles already in a roundabout.\n\n6. **Pedestrian Crosswalks:** Always stop for pedestrians at designated crosswalks. Pedestrians have the right of way.\n\n7. **Lane Discipline:** Stay in your lane and use indicators (blinkers) when changing lanes.\n\n8. **Overtaking:** Only overtake (pass) other vehicles when it is safe and legal to do so. In many places, overtaking is prohibited in certain zones like on curves, hills, or pedestrian crossings.\n\n9. **Use of Mobile Devices:** Most regions have laws against using mobile phones without a hands-free system while driving due to distraction risks.\n\n10. **Seat Belts:** All occupants of the vehicle must wear seat belts. This is a critical safety measure.\n\n11. **Driving Under Influence:** Never drive under the influence of alcohol or drugs. DUI laws are strict, with severe penalties including fines, suspension of driver\u2019s license, or even imprisonment.\n\n12. **Traffic Signs & Road Markings:** Pay attention to and obey all traffic signs and road markings. They provide important information about road conditions and regulations.\n\n13. **Emergency Vehicles:** Pull over or stop to allow emergency vehicles (police cars, ambulances, fire trucks) to pass.\n\n14. **School Zones:** Exercise extra caution in school zones, often with reduced speed limits during school hours.\n\n15. **Parking Rules:** Follow parking regulations and signs, such as no parking zones, handicapped spots, and time-limited parking areas.\n\n16. **Use of Headlights:** Use headlights at night or in conditions with poor visibility (fog, heavy rain).\n\n### Tips for Safe Driving:\n\n- **Stay Alert:** Pay attention to your surroundings and anticipate potential hazards.\n- **Avoid Distractions:** Keep away from activities that could divert your attention from driving, like eating or adjusting the radio.\n- **Road Conditions:** Adjust your driving according to road conditions. Slow down in bad weather and maintain a safe distance from other vehicles.\n- **Defensive Driving:** Always be prepared for potential mistakes by other drivers and drive cautiously.\n\n### Enforcement:\nTraffic laws are enforced by traffic police and other law enforcement agencies. Breaking these laws can result in fines, points on your driver\u2019s license, and in severe cases, imprisonment.\n\nRemember, traffic rules are designed to prevent accidents and ensure the safety of everyone on the road. Always keep safety as your top priority.",
